"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is crucial for 3D vision, yet non-Lambertian surfaces severely degrade performance by violating the linear assumption of epipolar plane images (EPIs). Existing methods heavily rely on high-resolution angular spectra or single-domain EPI models, which struggle with generalization in low angular resolution and multi-domain mixed scenarios. To address this, a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model was proposed to integrate physical priors with adaptive feature routing. Specifically, a three-layer angular signal decomposition was introduced, and geometric angular features with a random forest classifier were employed to achieve highly accurate material classification, providing reliable physical priors for guided training. Furthermore, a GeometricDualMask architecture was designed to separate and adaptively route features for different reflectance regions via dual masks. Coupled with domain-balanced sampling and a staged training strategy, the network optimized a physical prediction head regularized by phase and physical consistency losses. Extensive experiments demonstrate that the proposed method achieves an overall Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of 0.133 and a mixed urban MAE of 0.081, substantially outperforming baselines, while the material classifier yields an Area Under Curve (AUC) of 0.962. Ultimately, this work establishes a unified and robust framework for cross-domain light field depth estimation by bridging physical reflection models with deep dual-mask routing.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflectance, Epipolar plane images, Dual-mask routing, Domain-balanced sampling"